<p class="body">Repeat purchase rate is the input most affiliate creators undercount. A typical specialty coffee customer reorders every 2 to 4 weeks. Over twelve months, a single converted reader will place anywhere from 13 to 26 orders. Whether you capture commission on those reorders depends on the program's attribution model. Cookie-based attribution (the standard) only captures the first order in most cases; customer-ID attribution (less common, but offered by some direct programs) can capture repeats indefinitely. Read each program's fine print carefully: a 10% commission with customer attribution can easily out-earn a 20% commission with first-order-only attribution.</p>

<p class="body">Cookie windows matter more in coffee than in one-time purchase categories specifically because of the reorder cycle and the research-then-buy behavior of specialty coffee buyers. A 24-hour cookie window in fashion captures most buyers who were going to convert; a 24-hour window in specialty coffee misses the buyer who reads your origin guide on Tuesday, talks to their spouse about it Wednesday, and orders Saturday. ShareASale's default 30-day window and Impact.com's default 30-day window both work fine here. Anything shorter than 7 days is a red flag.</p>

<div class="callout">
  <p>The effective commission formula for coffee affiliate is roughly: headline rate * AOV * conversion rate * (1 + repeat purchase multiplier within cookie window). Headline rate alone is the worst possible way to rank programs. Most creators who chase the highest headline number end up underearning compared to creators who match program AOV and attribution model to their actual audience behavior.</p>
</div>

